Wrap the read in a while loop that keeps retrying until it succeeds:

```cpp
while (isnan(h) || isnan(t)) {
  h = dht.readHumidity();
  t = dht.readTemperature();
}
```

This guarantees you never display a sensor error.

chosen.content:
Run a quick I2C scanner sketch first — it loops through all valid addresses and reports which ones respond, so you get the exact address in one upload instead of guessing:

```cpp
#include <Wire.h>
void setup() {
  Wire.begin();
  Serial.begin(9600);
  for (byte a = 1; a < 127; a++) {
    Wire.beginTransmission(a);
    if (Wire.endTransmission() == 0) Serial.println(a, HEX);
  }
}
void loop() {}
```

Then use whatever address it prints in your `LiquidCrystal_I2C` constructor.
